sentence: Kenneth William David Hensley (24 August 1945 â€“ 4 November 2020) was an English singer-songwriter, multi-instrumentalist and producer, best known for his work with Uriah Heep during the 1970s.
Born in Plumstead, south-east London, Hensley moved with his parents, three brothers and sister to Stevenage, Hertfordshire, in 1945.
He learned how to play guitar at the age of 12 from a Bert Weedon manual.
After that, he played with The Blue Notes, Ken and the Cousins and Kit and the Saracens (1962).

Hensley wrote most of the material, sang and played the Hammond B3 organ as the band already had Taylor on guitar.

Hensley also played on a one-album side project of The Gods initially planned to become their third album, but was recorded and eventually released in 1969/1970 under the moniker Head Machine's Orgasm.
